The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, June 21, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, June 20: Small savings recorded a sharp rise of Rs 62,884 crore in 2003-04, driven mostly by the growth in the monthly income scheme, post office time deposits and Kisan Vikas Patra. The total outstandings of small savings increased from Rs 3,11,782 crore in 2002-03 to Rs 3,74,666 crore in 2003-04, according to data available with the Reserve Bank of India. The total receipts in March 2004 were the highest for the entire financial year at Rs 16,286 crore, followed by Rs 13,369 crore and Rs 13,336 crore in January and December, respectively.																								 Calcutta, June 20: Areva, a leading French energy company, has made a binding offer to acquire the transmission and distribution operations of Alstom Limited for 14.30 million euro (Rs 77.22 crore). Company officials said the offer, made with Alstom, France, was valid till December 31, 2004.																								 New Delhi, June 20: The Employees Provident Fund Organisation (EPFO) is all set to introduce a new accounting system enabling its subscribers to monitor their savings. The EPFO will change to double-entry accounting from the present single-entry system, after it is approved by the Comptroller and Auditor General of India.																								 New Delhi, June 20: Reliance Infocomm has embarked upon its second phase of expansion to add 60,000 km of optical fibre network to the existing 1 lakh km covering the entire country. It has planned to invest Rs 5,000 crore in the current financial year.																								 New Delhi, June 20: Radico Khaitan will set up a greenfield bottling plant in Uttaranchal and is targeting a 55 per cent rise in sales in this fiscal.
